courses.learning_outcomes:
學生完成本科目後，將能：
1. 從多角度理解19世紀中葉至今中、日兩國在政治、外交、經濟、軍事、民間社會、教育及文化等方面的關係的起伏發展，以及兩國關係對東亞地區發展的重要性；
2. 掌握有關現代中、日兩國關係的基本概念、知識及理論，如華僑和日僑的形成與發展、中國留日學生的活動、中國人的反日、附日活動、日本對華文化教育政策、兩國相互認識之變化、兩國間的多種糾紛，以及中國威脅論、中國機遇論等重要輿論的產生等；
3. 全面了解中、日兩國在各個方面的衝突和協作關係，尤其明白各領域的關係彼此影響互動的複雜性；
4. 透過參觀在香港日本國總領事館或在港日本文化宗教團體，認識日本官方對華的立場和政策，以及在華日本民間團體的多元化活動；
5. 透過講授課堂尤其導修課堂，養成研習中、日兩國關係的比較視野和批判分析思維，如評估中、日文獻中有關證據或事例在多少程度上說明兩國關係的某(些)方面，或檢查近人著作中的事例能否證明作者的論點；
6. 就現代中、日兩國關係的重要課題，參考各種文獻資料和近人著作，撰寫具邏輯性、連貫性及創意的評論短文；
7. 自行蒐集和分析有關中、日兩國關係的資訊，由此客觀地展望兩國關係的演進發展。
Upon completion of this course, students will be able to:
1. comprehend the development of Sino-Japanese relations in the aspects of politics, diplomacy, economic and military affairs, society, education and culture since the mid19 century and the importance of the relations to East Asia in multiple perspectives
2. master the basic concepts, knowledge and theories of modern Sino-Japanese relations including the evolution of the Chinese society in Japan and the Japanese society in China, the Chinese students’ activities in Japan, the Chinese resistance and collaboration with the Japanese, the Japanese cultural and education policy towards China, the mutual perception and disputes between the Chinese and the Japanese, and the theories of ‘China Threat’ and ‘China Opportunity’, etc;
3. thoroughly understand the conflicts and collaborations between China and Japan in different aspects and especially their interwoven interaction;
4. comprehend the standpoint and policy of the Japanese government towards China and various activities of the Japanese private organizations in China particularly by visiting Consulate-General of Japan or other cultural and religious organizations in Hong Kong;
5. develop comparative perspective and critical and analytical thinking on various aspects of modern Sino-Japanese relations, such as evaluating how far the evidence or examples in the Chinese and Japanese sources illustrate particular aspect(s) of Sino-Japanese relations, and checking whether they substantiate the writer’s claims;
6. write logical, coherent and creative essay on important issue(s) of modern Sino-Japanese relations based on different sources and recent studies;
7. collect and analyze various data about Sino-Japanese relations to look into the future relations objectively.

By the end of this course, students are expected:
1. ) to acquire knowledge on UN’s sustainable development goals, and to apply their knowledge to critically evaluate the current situations in Hong Kong, Asia and the world;
2. ) to be able to critically evaluate tourism as a means to achieve sustainable cities and communities;
3. ) to be able to scholarly compare Japan to other countries in relation to tourism;
4. ) to reflect on tourism development in Hong Kong.

(a) Dictating Japanese words and sentences precisely with the Kana syllabary;
(b) Understanding the basic pronunciation rules and tips to improve fluency;
(c) Conveying their meanings in Japanese in such a way that listeners can understand without difficulty;
(d) Delivering a naturally articulated short speech.

Students are expected to achieve the following three learning outcomes after studying this course:
(1) Have a deeper understanding of Japan's ACG industry and hence inspire a shared vision for local cultural industries;
(2) Analyze the interactive relationship between ACG culture and society;
(3) Apply academic theories to research and acquire the ability to analyze ACG works independently.

1) to develop a proper understanding of Japanese culture from a cultural historical point of view;
2) to properly articulate different topics with relevant historical contexts of Japan;
3) to critically examine popular and yet controversial theories and/or perceptive frameworks for analyzing Japanese culture; and
4) to understand the specificity and universality of Japanese culture.

Students are expected to achieve the following goals:
(a) Improving overall expressive skills and fluency in Japanese;
(b) Understanding the fundamentals of translation;
(c) Using commonly used vocabulary and grammatical items accurately and effectively;
(d) Grasping the overall structure of the Japanese language and its difference from Chinese.

Upon completion of the course, students are expected to achieve the following goals:
(i) Obtaining in-depth knowledge about the structure of the Japanese language;
(ii) Grasping ways of documenting and analyzing a language systematically;
(iii) Understanding differences and similarities between Japanese and other languages such as English and Chinese.

Upon completion of the course, students are expected to:
(i) Understanding how the Japanese language interrelates with culture and society;
(ii) Exploring the differences and similarities between Japanese and their own language (e.g., Chinese);
(iii) Applying the gained knowledge to understand people in Japan from linguistics and cultural perspectives.

Upon completion of the course, students are expected to:
1) understand the major points of Japanese history from pre-modern and modern eras;
2) deepen their understanding of Japanese society in its history, and today as well;
3) learn to write logical and coherent historical papers.

By the end of this course, students will:
1) understand the major points of Japanese history in the postwar era;
2) deepen their understanding of Japanese society in its history, and today as well;
3) learn to write logical and coherent historical papers.

